@David Connell Indeed, wild black walnuts are *very* hard nuts to crack. My implement of choice is a NEOLITH (really!), an approximately 6000-year-old black flint hammerstone I stumbled across while walking along the margin of a plowed field in Essex, U.K. Crafted from a flint nodule taken from the local chalk formation, this was someone's go-to tool in Neolithic England.

A modern option that works well is to slowly squeeze the nuts in a heavy vise until the shells succumb to the pressure. In any case, forget using a typical nutcracker.

An additional caution regarding that "thick, rubbery green rind"---when bruised or cut it exudes a "juice" that will stain your skin (and everything else) yellow-brown. The stain will last for a week or more---unless you are willing to remove several layers of skin! These husks were traditionally used to dye cloth in various shades of yellow-brown.

